    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Thank for the feedback.\n\nThe usecase in details:\n\nlet's say you have a categories panel like so:\n![2015-09-21-134540_288x271_scrot](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/123822/9991100/4ee10f80-6067-11e5-8e57-a120e8e46703.png)\n\nThen when there are no refinements because of the query, you would want to either:\n- hide the panel\n- display something like \"no categories for current query\"\n\nAnd that's not feasible right now.\n\nThe issue with our current API is that we decided to give the user the ability to provide a template PER refinement instead of being able to give a full template like this:\n\n``` mustache\n<div>\n  <div>categories</div>\n  {{#noRefinements}}No refinements dude!{{/noRefinements}}\n  {{#refinements}}\n    <div>{{title}}</div>\n  {{/refinements}}\n</div>\n```\n\nPossible solutions:\n- give a full template, but we again raise the issue of \"how do we know where the user clicked?\". Two solutions for this:\n  - force data-attributes to be set for us to target click events. like `<div data-refine></div>`\n  - provide full templates using http://wix.github.io/react-templates/\n- provide events like .on('refinements') on refinement list where you can subscribe to them and check data.length === 0\n\nFirst solution should be the chosen one because the \"events\" solution is a hack to solve something simple here.\n\nThoughts @algolia/javascript ?\n",
